'''1980 in radio''' involved some significant events. __TOC__
==Events== * 20 March – The [[pirate radio]] station ''[[Radio Caroline]]'' sinks. * April - [[WDLM-FM|WDLM]], a religious station based in [[East Moline, Illinois]], adds an FM signal at 89.3 MHz. It acts as both a repeater of WDLM's [[WDLM (AM)|AM signal]] (at 960 AM, which had been on the air since 1960) and adds additional programming. * 29 October – [[Jimmy Carter|President Carter]] on a visit to [[Pittsburgh]] gives a nationally broadcast campaign interview to [[KDKA (AM)|KDKA-AM]] of that city.
==Debuts== *[[Alex Bennett (broadcaster)|Alex Bennett]] returned to his native San Francisco to host a comedy-oriented morning show for [[album-oriented rock]] station [[KMEL]]. The show would last for the next 17 years on three different area radio stations.
==Closings== *11 February - ''[[Sears Radio Theater]] ends its run on [[CBS]]. Episodes were rebroadcast later in 1980 on [[Mutual Broadcasting System|Mutual]] as ''Mutual Radio Theater''.<ref name="dunningota">Dunning, John. (1998). ''On the Air: The Encyclopedia of Old-Time Radio''. Oxford University Press. {{ISBN|978-0-19-507678-3}}.</ref>
==Births== *9 October – [[Sarah X Dylan]], radio and television personality in [[Portland, Oregon]], United States, where she produced [[Rick Emerson#The Rick Emerson Show|''The Rick Emerson Show'']] on [[KUFO (AM)|KUFO]]
==Deaths== *7 January - [[Irene Beasley]], an [[United States|American]] singer and master of ceremonies best known for her work on old-time radio.<ref name="um">{{cite web|title=Irene Beasley Papers: Historical Note|url=http://digital.lib.umd.edu/archivesum/actions.DisplayEADDoc.do;jsessionid=88F8B5F53310CF743CE9041C153BAC5F?source=MdU.ead.lab.0017.xml&style=ead|website=University of Maryland Libraries|accessdate=19 March 2016}}</ref> *29 January - [[Jimmy Durante]], an American singer, [[pianist]], [[comedian]], and actor (born 1893)<ref name="coxotd">Cox, Jim (2008). ''This Day in Network Radio: A Daily Calendar of Births, Debuts, Cancellations and Other Events in Broadcasting History''. McFarland & Company, Inc. {{ISBN|978-0-7864-3848-8}}.</ref> *1 February - [[Jack Bailey (actor)|Jack Bailey]], 72, an [[United States|American]] actor and daytime [[game show]] host.<ref name=coxotd/> *4 February - Art Ballinger, actor, announcer and commercial spokesman.<ref name=coxotd/> *24 July – [[Peter Sellers]], English actor, comedian and radio personality (born 1925)
